Task 3 - Creating a ASP.NET Core application using Yeoman

Yeoman helps you to kickstart new projects, prescribing best practices and tools to help you stay productive.

To do so, it provides a generator ecosystem. A generator is basically a plugin that can be run with the yo command to scaffold complete projects or useful parts. By creating the ASP.NET Core generator, the goal is to provide an experience consistent with creating new ASP.NET Core projects and files in Visual Studio 2017.

In this task, you'll create a ASP.NET Core web application using Yeoman and the ASP.NET generator.- (In case you cant install or use Yeoman, you can still create the project using the new template command dotnet new mvc. That will create a basic MVC app but without Membership and Authorization)

  1. Now, install Yeoman and the ASP.NET generator using npm by executing the following command in a terminal.

npm install -g yo generator-aspnet

  1.  Open a terminal and run the following command.

yo aspnet

 

Running Yeoman ASP.NET generator

  1. Select the Web Application option.
  2. Next, you'll be prompted to name your application. Change the default name to use MyWebApp.

? What's the name of your ASP.NET application? (WebApplication)


  1. On proceeding, the generator will create an application with a structure similar to the following:

.

├─── Controllers

├─── Data

├─── Models

├─── Properties

├─── Services

├─── Views

│   ├─── Account

│   ├─── Home

│   ├─── Manage

│   └─── Shared

└─── wwwroot

     ├─── css

     ├─── images

     └─── js

  1. Restore the dependencies running the following commands in the terminal.

cd "MyWebApp"

dotnet restore

 


- Opening the site in VS Code


Visual Studio Code is a code editor redefined and optimized for building and debugging modern web and cloud applications. Additionally, it's free and available on your favorite platform - Linux, Mac OSX, and Windows.

In this task, you'll open and run the generated ASP.NET Core web application using Visual Studio Code.

  1. Open Visual Studio Code and select File > Open Folder... in the top menu to open the folder where you generated the project. When VS Code sees the csproj it will load it.
  2. Open the Startup.cs file and explore the different features that VS Code gives you like IntelliSense or features that traditionally found only in IDEs, such as Outlining, Find All References, and Go To Definition.

Exploring the VS Code features

  1. To execute the available commands, right-click the csproj file and select Open in Terminal to open a terminal where the file is located.
  2. Next, run the Web site by executing the dotnet restore and then dotnet run commands in the terminal.
  3. Open your favorite browser and browse to http://localhost:[port] to browse the site created.

Browsing the site
